00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.984
is the biggest challenge.

00:06:13.984 --> 00:06:14.650
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:06:14.650 --> 00:06:16.420
So let's talk about
food waste, which

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:18.910
is astounding in this country.

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:20.680
We heard a few
stats in the video,

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:23.320
but since you're the
expert, I would love

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:25.090
for you to talk more about it.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:26.872
Give us all of your
wisdom on food waste.

00:06:26.872 --> 00:06:27.580
ROBERT LEE: Sure.

00:06:27.580 --> 00:06:29.620
I think-- yeah.

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:34.040
When you think about food
waste, it is just food waste.

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:37.120
But when you think about
the different facets of what

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:41.380
that means, it's kind of mind
blowing because it's not just

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:42.380
about food waste.

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:44.440
It's about the
environmental impact

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:47.530
of that food waste, the
moral implications, what

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:50.912
that food has potential
to do, as well

00:06:50.912 --> 00:06:55.000
as the actual economic
impact of that.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.330
So on the environmental
issue, people don't really

00:06:58.330 --> 00:07:02.090
know that food waste
is one of the largest,

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:05.890
if not the largest component of
solid waste in the waste stream

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:09.880
and actually lands in landfills,
where it basically contributes

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:12.550
to carbon emissions through
methane gases, which

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:15.260
is actually 20 times
worse than carbon dioxide.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:18.850
And if you take food waste
as a kind of a global emitter

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:23.390
of carbon emissions and take it
out as if it's like a country,

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:26.090
it would rank third right
after the USA and China.

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:30.070
So just as a kind of
environmental issue

00:07:30.070 --> 00:07:35.060
after the fact of wasting food,
it's a huge kind of issue.

00:07:35.060 --> 00:07:38.290
But even going
before that supply

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:41.890
chain of actually wasting
the food, the amount of land,

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:45.715
amount of natural resources
used to grow that food is all

00:07:45.715 --> 00:07:47.140
wasted as well.

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:49.930
To grow the food that we
all eat in this country,

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:53.050
we use half the US land,
80% of the US fresh water.

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:55.525
10% of US energy budget
is used to transport

00:07:55.525 --> 00:07:59.220
that food in trucks and supply
chain and things like that.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:02.290
So all of that is wasted when
you waste 40% of the food

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:04.490
that you're producing.

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:08.790
So it's the environmental
impact on both sides.

00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:10.780
And so when you
combine those things,

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:16.566
it's a huge, huge,
non-negligible amount.

00:08:16.566 --> 00:08:18.190
And that's just the
environmental side.

00:08:18.190 --> 00:08:22.174
I mean, there's a whole bunch
of studies and things like that.

00:08:22.174 --> 00:08:23.590
And I think there
needs to be more

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:26.720
studies on the environmental
impact of food waste.

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:32.110
But the NRDC does a really
good job of telling people

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:33.485
about the issue of food waste.

00:08:33.485 --> 00:08:35.860
And one of the other things
that they mention, obviously,

00:08:35.860 --> 00:08:43.090
is the fact that the potential
of food waste is huge.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:46.080
It's a $165 billion
dollar problem in the US.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:48.190
It's obviously an
economic issue.

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:51.370
People are buying food
from the supermarkets

00:08:51.370 --> 00:08:52.900
and then wasting it.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:56.577
You might as well just
not buy 40% of the food

00:08:56.577 --> 00:08:58.160
that you're buying
at the supermarket.

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:02.491
So it's a huge
economic cost as well.

00:09:02.491 --> 00:09:04.240
Obviously, the US
energy budget and things

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:05.820
like that, that's
our taxes going

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:08.890
into food that's like going to
be wasted, like corn, subsidies

00:09:08.890 --> 00:09:09.580
for corn.

00:09:09.580 --> 00:09:12.640
Why do we do that?

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:18.346
Yeah, it's a huge, complex
issue, and implications

00:09:18.346 --> 00:09:20.470
that people don't really
think about when you think

00:09:20.470 --> 00:09:22.480
about it on a deeper level.

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:27.140
Obviously, along the lines
of potential food waste,

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:29.380
the food that's actually
going to waste obviously

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:30.520
can feed people.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:33.130
So people can be fed with that.

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:36.980
And what's more important
than feeding people that

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:41.290
are hungry and need that food if
you're going to be wasting it?

00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:43.420
And when you think
about the flip side

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:47.890
to that equation of
food waste and hunger,

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:50.600
49 million Americans
are food insecure.

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:54.790
And I mention in
the video, if you

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:57.190
think about the nutritional--
and obviously poverty is

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:00.090
a multi-faceted issue as well,
and it's not just nutrition--

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:03.280
but if you think about
just nutrition, reducing

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.554
30% of the wasted
food and bringing

00:10:06.554 --> 00:10:08.220
that directly to the
people who are food

00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:11.780
insecure would eliminate hunger,
which means that there's still

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:17.700
2/3 of food waste leftover that
needs to be reduced as well,

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:21.560
which is why there's the food
waste hierarchy of reducing it

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:24.050
on source and then
feeding people, feeding

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:27.410
animals, composting, and
then lastly, landfill.

00:10:27.410 --> 00:10:31.880
But I'm kind of going on
and on about food waste.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:33.900
You know, it's just so much.

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:35.300
It's so much.

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:40.400
And it's a huge, huge issue.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:42.950
SPEAKER 1: So how do we
compare to other countries?

00:10:42.950 --> 00:10:46.430
ROBERT LEE: The US
throws out a lot.

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:50.750
The average that people say
is 40%, according to reports.

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:54.440
On the worldwide level,
we waste about 30% of food

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:56.400
that we produce in the world.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:57.740
It's a lot.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:58.460
It's a lot.

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:02.760
And US is obviously
a little bit worse.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:04.610
But it's interesting
because the US,

00:11:04.610 --> 00:11:08.330
obviously, as one of
the developed nations,

00:11:08.330 --> 00:11:10.880
seems to waste a lot
more food on our end,

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:14.210
on the consumer end, which means
there's a lot of education that

00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:17.510
needs to happen in terms of
recognizing that food waste is

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:19.880
a problem, but also
doing something about it,

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:24.040
and doing easy things that
can be simply implemented

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:24.920
in all of our lives.

00:11:27.890 --> 00:11:30.830
In terms of developing nations,
a lot of their food waste

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:33.730
is happening on the
agricultural-- on the earlier

00:11:33.730 --> 00:11:36.620
side of the supply chain because
they don't have the technology

00:11:36.620 --> 00:11:38.870
or they don't have the
resources to implement

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:41.780
the kind of systems that
they have in the US.

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:46.490
So it's a shame, because
obviously the story that I just

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:49.760
mentioned about having
enough nutrition in the US

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:50.520
is the same.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:52.710
It's parallel across
the world as well.

00:11:52.710 --> 00:11:55.250
In the world, if we reduce
just one third of the food

00:11:55.250 --> 00:11:57.620
that we have going
to waste, that

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:02.030
could be easily enough to
eliminate food insecurity

00:12:02.030 --> 00:12:02.640
in the world.

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:07.911
So we talk about overpopulation
and the fear of feeding

00:12:07.911 --> 00:12:09.160
everyone and things like that.

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:11.840
But no one is thinking about
why not reduce the food

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:15.780
waste that we have going
on to solve that problem?

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:17.810
I mean, we don't have
to increase production.

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:20.120
We can just be more
efficient with the food

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:23.840
that we're already producing.

00:12:23.840 --> 00:12:27.140
I think overall, people
are becoming more and more

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:28.310
aware of the issue.

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:32.550
And I'm glad that people are
starting to pay attention.

00:12:32.550 --> 00:12:34.580
SPEAKER 1: So is food
waste getting better

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:35.780
or is it getting worse?

00:12:35.780 --> 00:12:36.887
Is it sort of the same?

00:12:36.887 --> 00:12:38.720
ROBERT LEE: I think
there's not as much data

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:41.600
as there needs to be in terms
of measurement and things

00:12:41.600 --> 00:12:42.140
like that.

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:44.420
I think even more
granular reports

00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:47.780
need to be published
in terms of where

00:12:47.780 --> 00:12:50.180
specifically in the supply
chain food is being wasted.

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:53.660
But in general, it seems like
the problem of food waste

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:56.480
is becoming more and more
of a mainstream issue

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:58.220
that people are
caring about, just

00:12:58.220 --> 00:13:01.490
in terms of the sheer number
of articles and attention

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:03.230
that people are
putting on food waste

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:05.960
has been increasing in the
past three or four years.

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:08.570
We're lucky in that we
just started in 2013,

00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:13.114
and it's been a huge increase
in the level of attention

00:13:13.114 --> 00:13:14.780
that people are putting
into food waste.

00:13:14.780 --> 00:13:17.450
So we do believe that
it's getting better.

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:20.797
But there's still obviously
a lot of work to be done.

00:13:20.797 --> 00:13:21.380
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:23.090
So you've started RLC.

00:13:23.090 --> 00:13:25.920
So how is RLC
solving the problem?

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:28.082
How is it different than
other organizations?

00:13:28.082 --> 00:13:28.790
ROBERT LEE: Yeah.

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:31.950
That's pretty much the number
one question we always get.

00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:35.540
But we started it in 2013
because, as I mentioned

00:13:35.540 --> 00:13:38.780
a little bit earlier,
we started to notice

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:43.320
that there was kind of a gap or
niche in the food rescue space.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:48.050
And when we started thinking
about outside the border of NYU

00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:50.150
and how food rescue
can be applied,

00:13:50.150 --> 00:13:53.540
we did a lot of research into
City Harvest and Food Bank

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:55.970
and even OzHarvest in
Australia and things

00:13:55.970 --> 00:13:58.650
like that to figure out what
solutions already existed

00:13:58.650 --> 00:14:01.170
and what was happening
and what was working.

00:14:01.170 --> 00:14:06.230
And so we realized that,
at least for New York City,

00:14:06.230 --> 00:14:09.120
the current solutions
typically had a minimum pound

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:10.630
requirement, where
they would not

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:15.150
go by for food that was under
a certain number of pounds.

00:14:15.150 --> 00:14:17.210
So we decided to
essentially target

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:22.100
that specific gap, that
niche market, and essentially

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:25.720
kind of use our solution
to that problem.

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:27.985
So we like to think of
ourselves as different in terms

00:14:27.985 --> 00:14:29.360
of that minimum
pound requirement

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:31.330
because we don't
have one, but also

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:36.200
in the fact that we use a kind
of technology-driven process

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:38.840
by using a web
application code on Ruby

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:41.690
on Rails that basically allows
people to kind of sign up

00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:43.940
online for any
pickup that they want

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:46.180
and crowdsource that
transportation problem,

00:14:46.180 --> 00:14:49.130
that distribution problem
between the excess food

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:50.210
and the hungry.

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:53.950
So yeah, there's a whole
bunch of other kind of things.

00:14:53.950 --> 00:14:56.960
I think one of the other
ways we're different

00:14:56.960 --> 00:14:59.570
is that we are
much more scalable

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:02.900
and that we have this kind
of platform that can just

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:07.790
be kind of basically put to use
in different geographic areas,

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:10.110
not just New York City.

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:13.230
And in other
models, you may have

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:15.510
to actually own
trucks, and own trucks

00:15:15.510 --> 00:15:17.610
and operate trucks in
each different city

00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:18.990
that you're running in.

00:15:18.990 --> 00:15:24.030
So we don't have
that kind of issue.

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:26.430
SPEAKER 1: So with RLC,
there's three parties.

00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:31.350
You have a food partner or a
donor, you have the volunteers,

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:32.800
and then you have the shelter.

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:37.730
So if I'm a food partner,
what does that look like?

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:39.270
ROBERT LEE: For a
food donor, we try

00:15:39.270 --> 00:15:43.300
to make it as easy as
possible because it's

00:15:43.300 --> 00:15:45.570
sometimes difficult
for food donors

00:15:45.570 --> 00:15:47.880
to feel comfortable
about donating food.

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:52.440
There's always so many stigmas
and myths around donating food.

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:54.210
So we try to make it
as easy as possible,

00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:59.170
and we cater to the
food donors' needs.

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:03.480
So as a food donor, when
they partner with RLC,

00:16:03.480 --> 00:16:06.930
they're first asked when
they throw out their food

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:08.800
and at what frequency.

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:11.790
So for example, just thinking
about any coffee shop,

00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:15.120
they may have pastries and
muffins at the end of the night

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:20.160
that they throw out when
they're closing out for the day.

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:23.159
And so they can tell
us, hey, we actually

00:16:23.159 --> 00:16:25.200
have these muffins and
pastries that we throw out

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:28.180
every single night at
9:00 PM when we close.

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:31.410
And what we can do is
essentially basically

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:35.010
ensure that we're there at
that time every single day

00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:37.220
and make it super easy for them.

00:16:37.220 --> 00:16:39.367
Instead of throwing it
out into a trash bag,

00:16:39.367 --> 00:16:40.950
just put it into a
different container

00:16:40.950 --> 00:16:42.900
that they can actually donate.

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:45.930
We do the transportation, we
do all the paperwork and things

00:16:45.930 --> 00:16:48.570
like that for them
and make it super easy

00:16:48.570 --> 00:16:51.870
for them to feel the
impact and understand

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:54.660
that their food is going to
the hungry without actually

00:16:54.660 --> 00:16:57.000
doing that much work.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.580
SPEAKER 1: You mentioned there's
myths about donating food.

00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:02.970
So you often hear that it's
illegal to donate food,

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:06.099
you can't do it, which is
why restaurants throw it out.

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:08.569
But that's not necessarily
true, especially with RLC.

00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:10.262
Can you talk more about that?

00:17:10.262 --> 00:17:10.970
ROBERT LEE: Yeah.

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:13.619
The number one pushback
we get from restaurants

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:17.849
and other food businesses
is that it's illegal,

00:17:17.849 --> 00:17:23.730
which is unfortunately just
widespread for some reason.

00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:26.460
There's a Bill Emerson
Good Samaritan Act of 1996

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:28.890
that's a federal law that
basically protects all food

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:33.570
donors from legal liability,
except in the case

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:37.540
of gross negligence, which is
basically extreme carelessness.

00:17:37.540 --> 00:17:39.750
So as long as they're adhering
to all the food safety

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:43.230
standards and ensuring that
they are a licensed food vendor

00:17:43.230 --> 00:17:45.370
and they know how to
handle food and donating

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:50.230
food in the right way,
there's no legal liability.

00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:53.390
Of course, if they throw
the food on the ground

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:56.280
and then donate, that's
obviously not the same thing.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:00.870
But the federal law
existed since 1996,

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:04.560
but all 50 states have
also passed state versions

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.430
of that same exact
Good Samaritan Law,

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:09.540
in some cases actually
helping to provide even more

00:18:09.540 --> 00:18:11.790
additional protections
for food donors.

00:18:11.790 --> 00:18:17.640
So it's kind of insane to hear
sometimes from restaurants

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:19.410
that they heard
that McDonald's got

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:22.740
sued for some reason or
another about food insecurity

00:18:22.740 --> 00:18:26.850
and people being sick off of
that food that they donated.

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:30.060
And there's no legal case.

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:33.330
There's nothing in the
case record about that.

00:18:33.330 --> 00:18:34.950
So it's just myths.

00:18:34.950 --> 00:18:38.530
And people have been doing
food rescue for over 35,

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:40.450
40 years now.

00:18:40.450 --> 00:18:43.650
And as long as we are all
adhering to the same food

00:18:43.650 --> 00:18:46.170
safety standards ensuring
that the food is safe,

00:18:46.170 --> 00:18:50.320
food can be donated and
can be completely fine.

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:53.760
So yeah, I think that's
the number one education

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:57.060
point that needs to happen
for people to really start

00:18:57.060 --> 00:19:01.410
understanding that licensed
food vendors, people that

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:04.080
can actually prepare the
food correctly and safely,

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:06.650
can donate that food.

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:08.310
SPEAKER 1: Good to know.

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:10.500
So it's so great
you have restaurants

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:12.660
that donate the food.

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:15.610
Do you report back any data,
you know, letting them know,

00:19:15.610 --> 00:19:17.751
this is how much you're wasting?

00:19:17.751 --> 00:19:18.750
Can you talk about that?

00:19:18.750 --> 00:19:19.458
ROBERT LEE: Yeah.

00:19:19.458 --> 00:19:23.010
So one of the benefits that
we provide for restaurants

00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:26.550
is the data piece
because there's

00:19:26.550 --> 00:19:30.560
a hierarchy of what
food waste should go to.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:32.430
I mentioned it a little bit.

00:19:32.430 --> 00:19:37.830
The number one thing is to
reduce it from the get-go.

00:19:37.830 --> 00:19:43.530
And for that, it pretty much
is thinking about creative ways

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:46.630
to use excess food
and things like that,

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:51.240
or just from the very production
of it, just don't produce it.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:56.430
And so we provide monthly data
in terms of days and number

00:19:56.430 --> 00:19:59.460
of pounds on how much
food is being donated

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:02.730
and thus would have been wasted
if they didn't work with us.

00:20:02.730 --> 00:20:04.320
And what that
allows the partners

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:09.070
to do is essentially analyze
that data and see, oh, hey,

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:13.540
I did not expect that much
food to be going to waste.

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:16.517
There's a lot of partners that
we've worked with initially

00:20:16.517 --> 00:20:18.350
that have given us
estimates like, oh, yeah,

00:20:18.350 --> 00:20:20.970
it's going to be
about 40 pounds.

00:20:20.970 --> 00:20:22.380
And it turns out
to be 40 pounds.

00:20:22.380 --> 00:20:24.213
For the first two, three
weeks, it turns out

00:20:24.213 --> 00:20:25.559
to be over 100 pounds.

00:20:25.559 --> 00:20:27.600
And that's because they're
just not measuring it.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:31.170
And just like any KPI, if
you're not measuring it,

00:20:31.170 --> 00:20:33.240
you can't do anything
about it, right?

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:38.260
And so basically having
that monthly data allows

00:20:38.260 --> 00:20:42.000
them to do not just looking at
and measuring out food waste

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.550
data, but also thinking
about, oh, hey,

00:20:44.550 --> 00:20:46.410
every Monday or
every weekend we seem

00:20:46.410 --> 00:20:50.430
to have much more food
waste than other days.

00:20:50.430 --> 00:20:52.680
And they can use that,
internalize that, and basically

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:54.510
reduce it on their own.

00:20:54.510 --> 00:20:59.310
Typically food donors
want to, obviously, keep

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:00.769
every single sale
that they have.

00:21:00.769 --> 00:21:03.060
So there's always going to
be a little bit of food that

00:21:03.060 --> 00:21:04.060
is going to go to waste.

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:07.430
But we typically see the
numbers kind of start

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:10.270
to come down and
plateau over time.

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:13.410
And that's one of the kind of
key things that we like to do,

00:21:13.410 --> 00:21:16.710
is ensure that we're measuring
our food waste in terms

00:21:16.710 --> 00:21:19.530
of our success metrics,
but also keeping

00:21:19.530 --> 00:21:21.690
in mind that we don't
want to necessarily

00:21:21.690 --> 00:21:23.670
have more pounds of food.

00:21:23.670 --> 00:21:29.460
We retain our main KPI
and main success measure

00:21:29.460 --> 00:21:32.130
as the number of
partners because that's

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:37.400
the real measure of success in
terms of what we're thinking.

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:39.150
SPEAKER 1: So before
we get to volunteers,

00:21:39.150 --> 00:21:41.670
let's talk about the shelters
or the food recipients.

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:43.730
What does it look like for them?

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:45.540
ROBERT LEE: So for
the food recipients,

00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:47.040
they're typically
homeless shelters,

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:49.510
soup kitchens, food
pantries, community centers,

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:50.440
things like that.

00:21:50.440 --> 00:21:53.790
They're 501(c)3
non-profit organizations.

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:59.880
And typically what happens
is, after we find a restaurant

00:21:59.880 --> 00:22:02.160
partner that has a certain
number of pounds of food,

00:22:02.160 --> 00:22:04.770
and they give us an expectation
of what type of food

00:22:04.770 --> 00:22:06.603
is going to go to waste
and things like that

00:22:06.603 --> 00:22:09.650
and can be donated, we
go and match that up.

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:12.700
We have great, wonderful
staff to help us do this.

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:16.890
And they basically
help match the food

00:22:16.890 --> 00:22:19.830
to what food is needed at
the homeless shelters, soup

00:22:19.830 --> 00:22:21.950
kitchens, and food pantries.

00:22:21.950 --> 00:22:25.140
And that way it can be a
regular, recurring food

00:22:25.140 --> 00:22:29.460
item that can basically
offset the food that they

00:22:29.460 --> 00:22:31.350
would normally buy.

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:33.660
So they can expect it.

00:22:33.660 --> 00:22:37.380
They know how much, typically,
on average, it's going to be,

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:41.230
and essentially they can take
that out of the food budget.

00:22:41.230 --> 00:22:44.670
And so that kind of
partnership really

00:22:44.670 --> 00:22:46.120
starts with the food donor.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:50.000
And on the food recipient
side, they receive it,

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.650
they give us a receipt
that basically helps us

00:22:52.650 --> 00:22:54.510
measure the number of pounds.

00:22:54.510 --> 00:22:57.990
And that basically goes
back to the food donor

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:00.552
and helps us
maintain our records.

00:23:00.552 --> 00:23:02.010
SPEAKER 1: And so
for the shelters,

00:23:02.010 --> 00:23:05.850
their goal is probably that
they never have to buy food.

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:07.851
That's the goal for them,
because they still do.

00:23:07.851 --> 00:23:09.183
ROBERT LEE: Yeah, they still do.

00:23:09.183 --> 00:23:10.373
SPEAKER 1: Have to buy food.

00:23:10.373 --> 00:23:11.456
ROBERT LEE: They still do.

00:23:11.456 --> 00:23:11.850
SPEAKER 1: Oy.

00:23:11.850 --> 00:23:13.260
ROBERT LEE: Yeah, it's insane.

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:15.430
There's just so
much food out there.

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:18.792
But it's always about
the right type of food,

00:23:18.792 --> 00:23:20.250
because different
homeless shelters

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:21.916
have different
requirements because they

00:23:21.916 --> 00:23:23.076
do different services.

00:23:23.076 --> 00:23:25.200
Like some of them do just
breakfast or some of them

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:26.960
do just dinner.

00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:30.130
And so bringing a bunch
of bagels to someone

00:23:30.130 --> 00:23:33.190
that just does dinner
is not helpful.

00:23:33.190 --> 00:23:34.640
So it's just making
that matching.

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:42.360
And that's kind of where we
can make that matching happen.

00:23:42.360 --> 00:23:43.630
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:23:43.630 --> 00:23:44.130
OK.

00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:47.630
So let's talk about volunteers
because without volunteers,

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:50.300
the organization
doesn't really run.

00:23:50.300 --> 00:23:53.510
I mean, there are other reasons.

00:23:53.510 --> 00:23:57.749
So what does it look like if you
are a volunteer, if you sign up

00:23:57.749 --> 00:23:58.290
to volunteer?

00:23:58.290 --> 00:24:01.200
ROBERT LEE: So anyone
can go online and sign up

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:04.290
to volunteer at Rescuing
Leftover Cuisine.

00:24:04.290 --> 00:24:08.580
It's just www.rescuingleft
overcuisine.org/calendar.

00:24:08.580 --> 00:24:10.980
And there's basically a
list of all the events

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:12.930
that we have in your region.

00:24:12.930 --> 00:24:19.980
And essentially the
events or rescues

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:23.490
are listed in
chronological order

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:25.990
and in different locations
within your region.

00:24:25.990 --> 00:24:28.545
So for example, in New
York City, there's FiDi,

00:24:28.545 --> 00:24:31.410
there's Midtown, there's Upper
West Side, Upper East Side.

00:24:31.410 --> 00:24:33.390
And essentially
people can filter down

00:24:33.390 --> 00:24:36.120
and look on a map view
as well and figure out

00:24:36.120 --> 00:24:41.100
what time and location
they're available to help out.

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:43.830
These pickups are
volunteer opportunities

00:24:43.830 --> 00:24:46.380
that are really easy to kind
of fit into your schedule

00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:49.947
because it's just 30 minutes
of your time to an hour.

00:24:49.947 --> 00:24:51.780
So you can do it easily
on your way to work,

00:24:51.780 --> 00:24:54.740
on your way between
classes or between the gym

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:57.120
and other things, or
in place of the gym.

00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:01.110
And you essentially can
help make direct impact

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:02.820
because you're going
to actually see--

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:05.250
after you sign up you'll get
an automated confirmation

00:25:05.250 --> 00:25:08.250
e-mails and all this, and you'll
get the contact information

00:25:08.250 --> 00:25:10.540
of the person who's going
to be leading your event.

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:12.970
And once you meet
with everyone, you

00:25:12.970 --> 00:25:16.366
can actually see the actual food
that's about to go to waste.

00:25:16.366 --> 00:25:17.740
The restaurant's
cleaning up, you

00:25:17.740 --> 00:25:22.030
get to see the aluminum tins
or bags and things like that.

00:25:22.030 --> 00:25:25.720
And you can actually rescue
that and walk it over.

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:28.675
Sometimes it will be
15 minutes walking,

00:25:28.675 --> 00:25:30.550
sometimes it will be
five minutes of walking.

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:33.010
Sometimes it will be
a little bit more,

00:25:33.010 --> 00:25:34.140
25 minutes of walking.

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.540
But it will be within
that neighborhood,

00:25:37.540 --> 00:25:38.610
same neighborhood.

